{"id": 61410, "acmi_id": "igdb-121", "title": "Minecraft", "title_annotation": "", "slug": "minecraft", "creator_credit": "", "credit_line": "", "headline_credit": "2011", "record_type": "work", "type": "Videogame", "is_on_display": false, "last_on_display_place": null, "last_on_display_date": null, "is_context_indigenous": false, "material_description": "", "unpublished": false, "first_production_date": "2011-10-07T11:00:00+11:00", "brief_description": "<p>Minecraft is an open world game that has no specific goals for the player to accomplish, allowing players a large amount of freedom in choosing how to play the game however, there is an achievement system. The gameplay by default is first person, but players have the option to play in third person mode. The core gameplay revolves around breaking and placing blocks. The game world is essentially composed of rough 3D objects—mainly cubes—that are arranged in a fixed grid pattern and represent different materials, such as dirt, stone, various ores, water, and tree trunks. While players can move freely across the world, objects and items can only be placed at fixed locations relative to the grid. Players can gather these material blocks and place them elsewhere, thus allowing for various constructions.</p>", "constellations_primary": [], "constellations_other": [{"id": 142, "name": "New ways of seeing", "description": "The 3D worlds presented through the stereoscopic viewer are part of an ongoing fascination with immersive imagery."}], "recommendations": [], "title_for_label": "<p>Minecraft</p>", "creator_credit_for_label": "", "headline_credit_for_label": "<p>2011</p>", "description": "", "description_for_label": [], "credit_line_for_label": "", "details": [{"label": "Formats/platforms", "display_values": ["PC (Microsoft Windows)", "PlayStation 4", "Xbox One", "Mac", "Android", "iOS", "PlayStation Network", "Nintendo Switch", "PlayStation 3", "Xbox 360", "Linux", "PlayStation Vita", "Wii U", "Windows Phone", "Lightw